Here's a concise C program that implements the bubble sort algorithm to sort a list of integers:

```c
#include <stdio.h>

void bubbleSort(int arr[], int n) {
    for (int i = 0; i < n-1; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < n-i-1; j++) {
            if (arr[j] > arr[j+1]) {
                // Swap elements
                int temp = arr[j];
                arr[j] = arr[j+1];
                arr[j+1] = temp;
            }
        }
    }
}

int main() {
    int arr[] = {64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90};
    int n = sizeof(arr)/sizeof(arr[0]);

    bubbleSort(arr, n);

    printf("Sorted array: ");
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        printf("%d ", arr[i]);
    }
    return 0;
}
```

This program:
1. Defines a `bubbleSort` function that implements the algorithm
2. Uses nested loops to compare and swap adjacent elements
3. Includes a `main` function with a test case
4. Prints the sorted array

The time complexity is O(n²) in the worst case.

Here's a concise JavaScript program that returns the nth Fibonacci number using an iterative approach (which is efficient with O(n) time and O(1) space):

```javascript
function fibonacci(n) {
    if (n <= 1) return n;
    let a = 0, b = 1;
    for (let i = 2; i <= n; i++) {
        [a, b] = [b, a + b];
    }
    return b;
}

