Here's a Java program that uses multithreading to calculate the sum of even Fibonacci numbers and the product of odd Fibonacci numbers up to a given limit:

```java
import java.math.BigInteger;

public class FibonacciThreads {
    private static final int LIMIT = 1000; // Change this to your desired limit
    private static volatile BigInteger evenSum = BigInteger.ZERO;
    private static volatile BigInteger oddProduct = BigInteger.ONE;

    public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
        Thread evenThread = new Thread(() -> {
            BigInteger a = BigInteger.ZERO, b = BigInteger.ONE;
            while (a.compareTo(BigInteger.valueOf(LIMIT)) <= 0) {
                if (a.mod(BigInteger.TWO).equals(BigInteger.ZERO)) {
                    evenSum = evenSum.add(a);
                }
                BigInteger next = a.add(b);
                a = b;
                b = next;
            }
        });

        Thread oddThread = new Thread(() -> {
            BigInteger a = BigInteger.ZERO, b = BigInteger.ONE;
            while (a.compareTo(BigInteger.valueOf(LIMIT)) <= 0) {
                if (!a.mod(BigInteger.TWO).equals(BigInteger.ZERO)) {
                    oddProduct = oddProduct.multiply(a);
                }
                BigInteger next = a.add(b);
                a = b;
                b = next;
            }
        });

        evenThread.start();
        oddThread.start();

        evenThread.join();
        oddThread.join();

        System.out.println("Sum of even Fibonacci numbers up to " + LIMIT + ": " + evenSum);
        System.out.println("Product of odd Fibonacci numbers up to " + LIMIT + ": " + oddProduct);
    }
}
```

Key features of this implementation:
1. Uses two threads - one for even sum calculation and one for odd product calculation
2. Uses `BigInteger` to handle large Fibonacci numbers and avoid overflow
3. Both threads generate Fibonacci sequence independently
4. `volatile` variables ensure visibility of updates between threads
5. `join()` ensures main thread waits for both calculations to complete
6. Each thread checks the Fibonacci numbers against the limit and performs its respective calculation

Note that for very large limits, the product of odd Fibonacci numbers will grow extremely quickly and may become impractical to compute.

